    <text>
        <body>
            <div><opener><salute>Dear Sir</salute></opener>
                
                <p>That many happy returns of this season may attend you is the united wish of this family.</p>
                
                <p>I shall not trouble you with attending on the affair of the <unclear>hollies</unclear> which is made up on honorable terms. The 
                    advertisement is gone to the post,<note type="editorial">This advertisement of 4 January 1791 has not been identified.</note> 
                    &amp; I hope the example will be followed by y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> county. If I omit any <unclear>atrititive</unclear> 
                    men it is thro' forgetfulness. <persName ref="pe0819">Messrs Smalley &amp; Co</persName> desire me to add a<del><gap reason="illegible" unit="letters" quantity="1"/></del> declaration on their part to be printed at the foot of our advertisement. Let us be civil, 
                    but firm.</p>
              
                <p>Adieu</p>
                
                <closer><salute>Y<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> faithfully
                </salute>
                    <signed><persName ref="pe0232">Tho. Pennant.</persName></signed></closer>
                <dateline><placeName ref="pl0001">Downing</placeName> Jan<hi rend="superscript">y</hi> 4<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1791</dateline>
                
            </div>
            
            <div>
                <p><address><addrLine><persName ref="pe0803">John Lloyd esq<hi rend="superscript">r</hi></persName><lb/> 
                    <placeName ref="pl1369">Wŷg Fair</placeName> ––––––
                    </addrLine></address></p>
